The literary magic of Harry Potter
PRINCETON – This summer, readers around the world marked the 20th anniversary of the first edition of J.K. Rowling’s Harry Potter series – Harry Potter and the Philosopher’s Stone (known as Harry Potter and the Sorcerer’s Stone in the United States) – with celebrations at literary festivals and bookstores. They had ample reason to celebrate.
Since the young magician first appeared on June 26, 1997, this "boy who lived" has become a symbol of resilience and endurance.
Over the past 20 years, the Harry Potter series has expanded to include seven novels, translated into more than 70 languages, and sold a total of 450 million copies.
Based on this book, eight movies have earned a total of $7 billion, while Harry Potter-themed toys and merchandise have generated an additional $7 billion in revenue.
It is difficult to imagine a day when global audiences are not captivated by J.K. Rowling's works for readers of a specific age and those with a literary mindset.
Therefore, I am always amazed to recall how my students reacted to J.K. Rowling's "Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone" in the fall of 1999—their response was poor—when I had included it in the syllabus for my popular literature course at Princeton University. Since 1993, I have been teaching a series of courses on bestsellers in America.
This course studies popular works from the 17th century to the present, inviting students to reflect on why and in what ways these bestsellers attract their audiences.
At the end of each semester, I have students choose a final book that represents popular tastes.
In 1999, they chose the first Harry Potter novel.
That year, Hurricane Portia made a fierce impact on the US coastline.
In June, the U.S. publisher of the series rushed to push the hardcover edition of Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets, the second installment of the Harry Potter series, into bookstores.
The institution also published the third book in this series, Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban, and the paperback edition of Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone on September 8th.
By the end of the month, J.K. Rowling's novel had dominated the top three spots on The New York Times Best Seller list for novels, while the paperback edition of Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone topped the best-selling paperback list.
Time magazine even featured this bespectacled wizard on its cover.
The image of Harry Potter can be seen everywhere where my gaze falls.
My students can't wait to know what drives such fervor.
Oh my, they are utterly disappointed.
In their view, the Harry Potter series is merely second-rate gibberish, falling far short of classics like The Chronicles of Narnia or The Lord of the Rings, which they hold dear from their own childhoods.
Though their childhoods have only recently passed a few short years ago, they criticize Harry Potter as many notorious adult critics do: as "piffle" (or "made-up nonsense"), "poorly written," "predictable," and "irritating."
Sure, please provide the Chinese sentence that you would like translated.
In their view, Harry lacked both wonder and wit and warmth.
The students' resentment surprised me, but with hindsight, there was nothing to fuss about.
Although adults have constituted a significant portion of the Harry Potter audience from the beginning, these students are precisely in the wrong age bracket to objectively recognize the Harry Potter phenomenon.
They were past the age of wanting new children’s literature but not quite old enough to have their own kids (I had just become a parent myself at the time), and they were eager to insist that while the Harry Potter series was now hugely popular, it would soon be forgotten.
In the autumn of the second year, that is, in 2000, the next batch of students also chose Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone as their end-of-term analysis book, just like their predecessors, they confidently rejected the book.
Let's fast-forward to spring 2007.
After suspending the course for several years, I taught "Bestsellers in America" again.
When students chose their end-of-term analytical book, they selected "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone."
And I am prepared to withstand their criticism.
But this time, their comments were very positive.
These are new-generation students, born between 1986 and 1989, who did not read J.K. Rowling's works as college students but were only teenagers just beginning their teenage years. This means they grew up alongside Harry, Ron, and Hermione.
The same thing happened in the autumn of 2010.
For these students, "We Grew Up With Harry Potter" has become a motto rather than a label.
Will Harry disappear from人们的对话似乎在半途中被打断了，正确的句子应该是：Will Harry disappear from memory?
The translation of the sentence "只要我们还活着，就不可能。" from Chinese to English is:  "As long as we are alive, it is impossible."  However, this translation might sound a bit awkward in English due to the structure of the original Chinese sentence. A more natural way to express this idea could be:  "It is impossible as long as we are alive."
Since 2010, I have taught bestseller courses twice, and on both occasions, the students chose non-Harry Potter novels for their final reviews.
