Based on the comments from my course "Children's Literature" where Harry Potter books are studied, this seems unlikely.
Now, I have chosen to include a Harry Potter novel in the syllabus, but I did not opt for Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone; instead, I chose Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban – which is my favorite book in the series and marks the transition from children's literature to young adult fiction. The book offers a nuanced exploration of themes such as loyalty, betrayal, anger, and compassion.
My many students also like this book best.
But how long can the popularity of the Harry Potter series sustain?
Whenever I teach children's literature, I first conduct a poll: "Which books on the syllabus did you read when you were a child?"
In 2010, 86% of people had read "Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban."
In 2012, this figure rose to 94%.
But in the years that followed, the percentage continued to decline — it was 87% in 2014 and had dropped to 81% in 2016.
These are not science, I know.
But I am curious: Will the percentage of students who have read Harry Potter drop below 80% when I teach "Children's Literature" again next spring?
Could it turn out that the students were right in 1999-2000, that Harry Potter's status has been declining continuously and that it will never become a classic work?
Is there still a balance point ahead where the percentage can stabilize and no longer decline?
Maybe Harry's 40th anniversary will tell us the answer.
Until then, I had always been delighted to invite him into my classroom.
